    crc16-modbus
    Modbus RTU serial protocol
    Width:   16 bits (2 bytes)
    Poly:    0x8005
    Init:    0xFFFF
    RefIn:   True
    RefOut:  True
    XorOut:  0x0000
    Check:   0x4B37  (CRC of '123456789')
    Spec:    CRC:crc16-modbus_le  or  CRC:crc16-modbus_be
    Algorithm: crc16-modbus
    Data:      01 03 00 00 00 0A  (6 bytes)
    CRC:       0xCDC5
    Bytes LE:  C5 CD
    Bytes BE:  CD C5
    Algorithm: crc8-maxim
    Data:      48 65 6C 6C 6F  (5 bytes)
    CRC:       0xEB
    Byte:      EB
    Algorithm: crc32
    Data:      01 02 03 04  (4 bytes)
    CRC:       0xB63CFBCD
    Bytes LE:  CD FB 3C B6
    Bytes BE:  B6 3C FB CD
  === section: help ===
/echo {on | off} - Toggle REPL command echo, or set on/off. Output is not affected.
  Subcommands:
    /echo.quiet <on | off> - Set echo on/off silently (no output message).
/port {name} - Serial port tools: open, close, list, configure.
  Subcommands:
    /port.baud_rate {value} - Show or set baud rate.
    /port.break {duration_ms} - Send a break signal (default 250ms).
    /port.byte_size {value} - Show or set data bits.
    /port.cd - Show Carrier Detect state (read-only).
    /port.close - Disconnect from the serial port.
    /port.cts - Show CTS state (read-only).
    /port.dsr - Show DSR state (read-only).
    /port.dtr {0|1} - Show or set DTR line (hardware only).
    /port.flow_control {mode} - Show or set flow control (none/rtscts/xonxoff/manual).
    /port.info - Show port status, serial parameters, and hardware lines.
    /port.list - List available serial ports.
    /port.open {name} - Connect to the serial port (optional port override).
    /port.parity {value} - Show or set parity.
    /port.ri - Show Ring Indicator state (read-only).
    /port.rts {0|1} - Show or set RTS line (hardware only).
    /port.stop_bits {value} - Show or set stop bits.
/cfg {key {value}} - Show or change config values.
    Three modes:
      /cfg              - show all config key/value pairs
      /cfg baud_rate    - show current value of 'baud_rate'
      /cfg baud_rate 115200 - change with confirmation dialog

    Type is auto-detected from the existing value (int, float,
    bool, string). Bool accepts: true/false, yes/no, on/off, 1/0.
    Changes are saved to the JSON config file.

    Use /cfg.auto to set values without confirmation (for scripts).
  Subcommands:
    /cfg.auto <key> <value> - Set immediately (no confirmation).
    /cfg.cap - List files in cap/.  ...
    /cfg.configs - List all config files.
    /cfg.dump - Print current config as JSON to the terminal.
    /cfg.explore - Open config directory in file explorer.
    /cfg.info {--display} - Show project summary. --display opens full report.
    /cfg.plugin - List files in plugin/.  ...
    /cfg.prof - List files in prof/.  ...
    /cfg.proto - List files in proto/.  ...
    /cfg.run - List files in run/.  ...
    /cfg.ss - List files in ss/.  ...
    /cfg.viz - List files in viz/.  ...
/proto.crc - Browse and compute CRC algorithms.
  Subcommands:
    /proto.crc.c <name> - Generate C source code for a CRC algorithm.
    /proto.crc.calc <name> {data} - Compute CRC over hex bytes, text, or file.
    /proto.crc.help <name> - Show algorithm parameters and description.
    /proto.crc.list {pattern} - List algorithms (optional glob filter).
    /proto.crc.python <name> - Generate Python source code for a CRC algorithm.
    /proto.crc.rust <name> - Generate Rust source code for a CRC algorithm.
/var {name} - List user variables, or show one by name.
    User-defined variables use $(NAME) syntax (case-sensitive).

    Setting variables (no / prefix needed):
      $(PORT) = COM7
      $(ADDR) = 01

    Using variables in commands:
      /print $(PORT)
      AT+PORT=$(PORT)

    Commands:
      /var               - list all variables
      /var PORT          - show one variable (bare name or $(PORT))
      /var.set PORT val  - set a variable (bare name or $(PORT))
      /var.clear         - clear all variables

    Dynamic variables (current clock at point of use):
      $(DATE)              - current date (YYYY-MM-DD)
      $(TIME)              - current time (HH:MM:SS)
      $(DATETIME)          - current date and time

    Launch variables (frozen when the app starts):
      $(LAUNCH_DATE)       - app start date
      $(LAUNCH_TIME)       - app start time
      $(LAUNCH_DATETIME)   - app start date and time

    Session variables (set once per script launch, frozen):
      $(SESSION_DATE)      - script start date
      $(SESSION_TIME)      - script start time
      $(SESSION_DATETIME)  - script start date and time

    Config variables (resolved paths from current config):
      $(CFG)               - config name (e.g. demo)
      $(CFG.DIR)           - config directory (resolved)
      $(CFG.FILE)          - config file path (resolved)
      $(CFG.LOG_FILE)      - log file path (resolved)
      $(CFG.RUN_DIR)       - scripts directory
      $(CFG.PROTO_DIR)     - protocol test directory
      $(CFG.PLUGIN_DIR)    - plugin directory
      $(CFG.SS_DIR)        - screenshot directory
      $(CFG.CAP_DIR)       - capture directory
      $(CFG.PROF_DIR)      - profile directory
      $(CFG.VIZ_DIR)       - visualizer directory
      $(CFG.PORT)          - serial port name
      $(CFG.BAUD)          - baud rate
      $(CFG.PORT_CFG)      - port config (e.g. 9600 8N1)
      $(CFG.PORT_FULL)     - full connection (e.g. COM4 9600 8N1)

    Escaping (when your data contains literal $):
      \$(PORT)           - literal $(PORT) (not expanded)
      /raw $(GPS),NMEA,0 - send entire line verbatim (no expansion)

    Scope: variables persist for the session. They are cleared
    automatically when a script is launched from the Scripts button
    or the Run menu, but NOT when /run is typed interactively.
    Use /var.clear to reset manually.
  Subcommands:
    /var.clear - Clear all user variables.
    /var.set <NAME> <value> - Set a user variable.
/cap - Data capture tools.
  Subcommands:
    /cap.bin <file> bytes=<N> {mode=new|append} {timeout=<dur>} {cmd=... (must be last)} - Capture raw binary bytes to a
file.
    /cap.hex <file> fmt=<spec> records=<N> {mode=new|append} {sep=...} {echo=on|off} {timeout=<dur>} {cmd=... (must be
last)} - Capture hex text lines, decode with format spec to CSV.
    /cap.stop - Stop an active capture.
    /cap.struct <file> fmt=<spec> records=<N> {mode=new|append} {sep=...} {echo=on|off} {timeout=<dur>} {cmd=... (must
be last)} - Capture raw bytes, decode with format spec to CSV.
    /cap.text <file> timeout=<dur> {mode=new|append} {echo=on|off} {cmd=... (must be last)} - Capture serial text to a
file for a timed duration.
  === section: help.run ===
â”€â”€ Scripts â”€â”€
  /run at_demo                                         Walks through all demo device commands
  /run doc_screenshots                                 Generate documentation images
  /run expect_test                                     Expect command test
  /run gps_demo                                        Query simulated GPS receiver
  /run smoke_test                                      Smoke test for demo device
  /run status_check                                    Quick status check
  /run var_demo                                        Set variables and use them in commands
  /run welcome                                         Runs on connect via on_connect_cmd config
  8 scripts.
  === section: help.plugin ===
â”€â”€ Application â”€â”€
  /cli                                                 Already in CLI mode.
  /clr                                                 Clear the terminal screen (alias for /cls).
  /color                    {on|off}                   Show or toggle color output.
  /delay                    <duration>                 Wait for duration with progress bar (e.g. 500ms, 1.5s).  (1)
  /demo                                                Set up and switch to the demo device config.  (1)
  /raw                      <text>                     Send raw text to serial (no transforms or line ending).
  /run                      {filename}                 Run a script file, or list available scripts.  (1)
  /tui                                                 Switch to TUI mode.

â”€â”€ Application Plugins â”€â”€
  /cap                                                 Data capture tools.  (5)
  /cfg                      {key {value}}              Show or change config values.  (12)
  /cls                                                 Clear the terminal screen.
  /confirm                  {message}                  Show Yes/Cancel dialog; Cancel stops a running script.
  /echo                     {on | off}                 Toggle REPL command echo, or set on/off. Output is not affected.
(1)
  /edit                     <filename>                 Open a project file in the system editor.  (6)
  /env                      {pattern}                  Manage $(env.NAME) expansion for CLI commands.  (3)
  /exit                                                Exit termapy.
  /grep                     <pattern>                  Search the scrollback for lines matching a pattern
(case-insensitive regex).
  /help                     {cmd}                      List REPL commands, or show help for one command.  (5)
  /include                  ... /help include          Include device command help from JSON response.  (4)
  /os                       <cmd>                      Run a shell command and show output (10s timeout). e.g. /os dir
  /ping                     ... /help ping             Send a command and measure response time.  (1)
  /port                     {name}                     Serial port tools: open, close, list, configure.  (16)
  /print                    <text>                     Print a message to the terminal.  (1)
  /proto                                               Binary protocol tools: send, run, debug, hex, crc, status.  (7)
  /seq                                                 Show sequence counters.  (1)
  /show                     <name>                     Show a file.  (1)
  /show_line_endings        {on | off}                 Toggle visible \r \n markers in serial output for line-ending
troubleshooting.
  /ss                                                  Screenshot tools: save SVG/text, show folder.  (3)
  /stop                                                Abort a running script.
  /var                      {name}                     List user variables, or show one by name.  (2)
  /ver                                                 Show termapy version.
  /verbose                  {on|off}                   Show or toggle verbose status output.
  /xfer                                                File transfer settings.  (1)
  /xmodem                                              XMODEM file transfer.  (2)
  /ymodem                                              YMODEM file transfer (batch, 1K blocks).  (2)
